Ah, metasomatism. Another tedious process the universe insists on performing, as if simply existing wasn't enough. Fine, if you insist on knowing. Here’s a slightly more elaborate explanation, though I can't promise it will make the cosmos any less underwhelming.

***

# Metasomatism: The Chemical Overhaul of [Rock](/Rock_(geology))

Metasomatism (derived from the venerable [Greek](/Ancient_Greek) μετά *metá*, signifying "change," and σῶμα *sôma*, meaning "body") refers to the profound chemical alteration of a [rock](/Rock_(geology)) orchestrated by the relentless passage of [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) and various other reactive fluids. It's not just a superficial wash; it’s a fundamental compositional restructuring, a complete molecular makeover. [^1] Traditionally, this phenomenon is meticulously defined as a form of [metamorphism](/Metamorphism) that inherently involves a significant shift in the overall [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition) of the rock, consciously excluding mere volatile components like [water](/Water) or [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) which are often transient. [^2]

At its core, metasomatism is the systematic replacement of one pre-existing [rock](/Rock_(geology)) by another, fundamentally distinct in both its [mineralogical](/Mineralogy) and [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition). The original [minerals](/Mineral) that once proudly constituted the rock are meticulously dissolved away, while, in a seemingly synchronized act, new [mineral](/Mineral) formations are precisely deposited in their vacated spaces. This intricate dance of [dissolution](/Dissolution_(chemistry)) and deposition occurs not in a chaotic slurry, but simultaneously, ensuring the [rock](/Rock_(geology)) remarkably maintains its solid, structural integrity throughout this transformative process. It's like rebuilding a house brick by brick, without ever letting it collapse.

The term "metasomatism" isn't entirely alone in its designation. Synonyms occasionally employed to describe this geological metamorphosis include "metasomatosis" [^3] and "metasomatic process." The term "metasomatose" itself is sometimes reserved for specifying particular, nuanced varieties of metasomatism, such as [Mg](/Magnesium)-metasomatose, indicating a significant influx of [magnesium](/Magnesium), or [Na](/Sodium)-metasomatose, highlighting the addition of [sodium](/Sodium). [^4] It seems even rocks can’t decide on a single identity.

## Genesis of Metasomatism: Fluids from the Deep

The driving force behind metasomatism is almost invariably the action of [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) fluids. These highly reactive aqueous solutions can originate from diverse geological sources, primarily stemming from either an [igneous](/Igneous) or a [metamorphic](/Metamorphism) genesis. Their passage, whether a slow seep or a forceful gush, is what dictates the extent and nature of the transformation.

Consider the [igneous](/Igneous_rock) realm, where the sheer heat and chemical potency are truly impressive. In these environments, metasomatism manifests in the creation of distinctive rock types such as [skarns](/Skarn) and [greisen](/Greisen). It also profoundly affects existing [hornfels](/Hornfels) within the [contact metamorphic aureole](/Contact_aureole) – that intensely altered zone immediately adjacent to an [intrusive rock](/Intrusive_rock) mass, like a [granite](/Granite) [pluton](/Pluton). Here, the magma acts as a chemical engine, driving fluids into the surrounding country rock, cooking and chemically re-sculpting it. A classic example of metasomatic alteration in an [igneous](/Igneous_rock) context can be observed in the metamorphosed [granite](/Granite) near [Stone Mountain](/Stone_Mountain), [Atlanta](/Atlanta), where metasomatic [albite](/Albite), [hornblende](/Hornblende), and [tourmaline](/Tourmaline) replace original minerals, a stark testament to the power of these chemical exchanges.

In the equally dynamic [metamorphic](/Metamorphism) environment, metasomatism is fundamentally propelled by the ubiquitous process of [mass transfer](/Mass_transfer). This involves the movement of chemical components from a volume of [metamorphic rock](/Metamorphic_rock) situated under conditions of higher [stress](/Stress_(physics)) and [temperature](/Temperature) towards a zone experiencing comparatively lower stress and temperature. Within this system, [metamorphic hydrothermal solutions](/Hydrothermal) function as the crucial [solvent](/Solvent), facilitating the dissolution, transport, and redeposition of various [mineral](/Mineral) constituents. One can visualize this on a grand scale: vast volumes of [metamorphic rocks](/Metamorphic_rock) deep within the [Earth's crust](/Crust_(geology)) undergo dehydration as hydrous [minerals](/Mineral) break down under increasing pressure and heat. This released fluid, now laden with dissolved [mineral](/Mineral) components, then percolates upwards into the shallower levels of the [crust](/Crust_(geology)), where it encounters different conditions and chemically changes, or "alters," the rocks it permeates. It’s an inconveniently efficient recycling system.

This underlying mechanism inherently implies that metasomatism is a quintessential example of "open system" behavior. This stands in stark contrast to the more traditional, classical definition of [metamorphism](/Metamorphism), which typically describes the *in-situ* [mineralogical](/Mineralogy) change of a rock without any appreciable alteration in its overall bulk [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition). However, because [metamorphism](/Metamorphism) almost invariably requires the presence of [water](/Water) to facilitate the complex array of metamorphic reactions, it is practically a given that [metamorphism](/Metamorphism) and metasomatism occur in conjunction, often inextricably linked.

Furthermore, precisely because metasomatism is fundamentally a [mass transfer](/Mass_transfer) process, its effects are not confined solely to the rocks that experience an *addition* of [chemical elements](/Chemical_element) and [minerals](/Mineral) or hydrous [compounds](/Chemical_compound). In every single instance, for a metasomatic rock to be formed, some other rock, somewhere, must also undergo a complementary metasomatic transformation. This might be as subtle as dehydration reactions with minimal apparent chemical change, but a change nonetheless. This concept is perhaps best illustrated by the formation of [gold ore deposits](/Ore_genesis). These precious deposits are the direct product of a highly focused concentration of fluids, often derived from many cubic kilometers of dehydrated [crust](/Crust_(geology)). These fluids, carrying dissolved [gold](/Gold) and other elements, migrate into much thinner, often intensely metasomatized and altered [shear zones](/Shear_zone) and [lodes](/Lode). While the vast source region of the fluids may appear largely chemically unaffected when compared to the dramatically hydrated and altered [shear zones](/Shear_zone), it is crucial to recognize that both regions must have undergone complementary metasomatism. One cannot exist without the other, a geological yin and yang.

## Metasomatism in the [Earth's Mantle](/Earth%27s_mantle)

The intricacies of metasomatism become even more pronounced and complicated within the profound depths of the [Earth's mantle](/Earth%27s_mantle). Here, the composition of [peridotite](/Peridotite), the dominant mantle rock, can be drastically altered at the extremely high temperatures prevalent there. This alteration is driven by the infiltration of various melts, specifically [carbonate](/Carbonate) and [silicate](/Silicate) melts, as well as by [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide)-rich and water-rich fluids, as comprehensively discussed by Luth (2003). [^5] The sheer scale and conditions within the mantle mean that metasomatism isn't just a surface phenomenon; it's a planetary-scale process.

Metasomatism is widely considered to be particularly critical in fundamentally changing the composition of mantle [peridotite](/Peridotite) situated beneath [island arcs](/Island_arc). This occurs as [water](/Water) and other volatile components are systematically driven out of the subducting [ocean](/Ocean) [lithosphere](/Lithosphere) during the process of [subduction](/Subduction). This released water, acting as a powerful solvent, ascends into the overlying mantle wedge, initiating widespread metasomatic reactions. Furthermore, metasomatism has also been posited as a crucial mechanism for enriching the source regions of certain [silica-undersaturated](/Normative_mineralogy) [magmas](/Magma), providing the necessary chemical ingredients for their unique compositions. [Carbonatite](/Carbonatite) melts, in particular, are frequently implicated as the primary agents responsible for the enrichment of mantle [peridotite](/Peridotite) in what geochemists refer to as [incompatible elements](/Incompatible_element) – those elements that struggle to fit into the crystal lattice of common rock-forming [minerals](/Mineral) and thus become concentrated in residual melts or fluids.

## Distinguishing Metasomatism from Other Endogenic Processes

Metasomatism bears superficial resemblances to other internal geological processes, but it is definitively separated by four distinct and essential features. [^6]

The first of these defining characteristics is the process of **ion-by-ion replacement** within existing [minerals](/Mineral). This isn't a violent shattering, but a meticulous, atomic-scale exchange. It occurs as new [minerals](/Mineral) precipitate from the metasomatic fluid simultaneously with the [dissolution](/Dissolution_(chemistry)) of the pre-existing [minerals](/Mineral). The rock doesn't melt and recrystallize; it transforms while remaining solid, a ghost of its former self.

The second crucial feature used to unequivocally identify metasomatism is the **preservation of the rock in its solid state** throughout the entire replacement process. Unlike melting, where a rock becomes a liquid and then solidifies, metasomatism maintains the structural integrity and often the original fabric of the parent rock, even as its chemical identity shifts dramatically. It’s a quiet, internal revolution.

The third distinctive feature sets metasomatism apart from mere isochemical [metamorphism](/Metamorphism). This is the **addition or subtraction of major [chemical elements](/Chemical_element)**, specifically beyond the simple gain or loss of volatile components like [water](/Water) (H₂O) and [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) (CO₂). If the bulk chemistry of the rock fundamentally changes, you're looking at metasomatism, not just a mineralogical rearrangement.

The final, and often most visually striking, feature is the formation of **distinct zones of metasomatism**. These zones are typically generated as a consequence of focused [magmatism](/Magmatism) and [metamorphism](/Metamorphism), and they often arrange themselves into a characteristic, predictable pattern known as a "metasomatic column." This column reflects the chemical gradients and reaction fronts established as fluids interact with the host rock, creating a series of concentric or layered alterations. It's a geological barcode, if you know how to read it.

## Types of Metasomatites: The Transformed Rocks

The resulting metasomatic rocks, often termed "metasomatites," can exhibit an astonishing degree of variety. Frequently, metasomatized rocks are pervasively, yet subtly, altered. In such instances, the only immediate evidence of this profound transformation might be a slight bleaching, a change in overall color, or a subtle shift in the crystallinity of micaceous [minerals](/Mineral). You'd almost miss it, if you weren't paying attention.

In these more enigmatic cases, characterizing the alteration often necessitates meticulous [microscope](/Microscope) investigation of the [mineral assemblage](/Mineral_assemblage) of the rocks. This allows geologists to identify the newly formed [minerals](/Mineral), detect any additional [mineral](/Mineral) growth, and observe subtle changes in the original protolith [minerals](/Mineral) – the ones that were there before the chemical intervention.

Sometimes, more robust geochemical evidence can be unearthed, unequivocally pointing to metasomatic alteration processes. This evidence usually manifests as anomalous concentrations of typically mobile and soluble [chemical elements](/Chemical_element), such as [barium](/Barium), [strontium](/Strontium), [rubidium](/Rubidium), [calcium](/Calcium), and certain [rare earth elements](/Rare_earth_elements). These elements, easily carried by fluids, become concentrated or depleted depending on the fluid chemistry and rock interaction. However, to properly characterize such alteration, it's absolutely essential to compare altered samples with their unaltered counterparts, providing a baseline for the chemical shift. Otherwise, you're just guessing.

When the metasomatic process becomes exceptionally advanced, it can lead to the formation of quite distinctive and recognizable metasomatites, including:

*   **[Chlorite](/Chlorite_group) or [Mica](/Mica) whole-rock replacement**: This often occurs within [shear zones](/Shear_zone), where intense deformation provides pathways for fluids. The existing [mineralogy](/Mineralogy) of the rock is completely recrystallized and replaced by hydrous [minerals](/Mineral) such as [chlorite](/Chlorite_group), [muscovite](/Muscovite), and [serpentine](/Serpentine_group). The original rock fabric might be preserved, but its chemical soul has been entirely swapped.
*   **[Skarn](/Skarn) and skarnoid rock types**: These are typically found immediately adjacent to [granite](/Granite) intrusions, particularly where the intrusive body comes into contact with highly reactive [lithologies](/Lithology) such as [limestone](/Limestone), [marl](/Marl), and [banded iron formation](/Banded_iron_formation). Skarns are often rich in calc-silicate [minerals](/Mineral) like [garnet](/Garnet) and [pyroxene](/Pyroxene), formed by the intense chemical exchange between the igneous fluids and the carbonate-rich host rock.
*   **[Greisen](/Greisen) deposits**: These form specifically within [granite](/Granite) margins and [cupolas](/Cupola_(geology)) – dome-like protrusions from the main [pluton](/Pluton). [Greisen](/Greisen) is characterized by the intense alteration of [feldspar](/Feldspar) and [biotite](/Biotite) to [quartz](/Quartz) and [muscovite](/Muscovite) ([sericite](/Sericite)), often associated with [tin](/Tin), [tungsten](/Tungsten), and [fluorine](/Fluorine) mineralization.
*   **[Rodingite](/Rodingite)**: This peculiar metasomatite is characteristic of [ophiolites](/Ophiolites), particularly their [serpentinized](/Serpentinized) [mafic](/Mafic) [dykes](/Dike_(geology)). [Rodingite](/Rodingite) typically comprises grossular-andradite [garnet](/Garnet), calcic [pyroxene](/Pyroxene), [vesuvianite](/Vesuvianite), [epidote](/Epidote), and [scapolite](/Scapolite). Its formation involves [calcium](/Calcium) metasomatism from fluids released during [serpentinization](/Serpentinization).
*   **[Fenite](/Fenite)**: A distinct variant of metasomatism, [fenite](/Fenite) is intimately associated with strongly alkaline or [carbonatitic](/Carbonatite) [magmatism](/Magmatism). It involves the introduction of a diverse array of [feldspars](/Feldspar) (often alkaline), sodic [pyroxenes](/Pyroxene) or [amphiboles](/Amphibole), and frequently includes unusual [minerals](/Mineral) that incorporate ordinarily [incompatible elements](/Incompatible_element) like [niobium](/Niobium), [zirconium](/Zirconium), and [rare earth elements](/Rare_earth_elements) that do not readily become incorporated into typical crystal lattices.
*   **Albitite**: This forms through the pervasive replacement of original [plagioclase](/Plagioclase) [feldspar](/Feldspar) by [albite](/Albite) ([albitization](/Albitization)). [^7] [^8] This process often involves the removal of [calcium](/Calcite) and the addition of [sodium](/Sodium) by circulating [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) fluids, leading to a rock composed predominantly of [albite](/Albite).

## Metasomatism in Mantle [Peridotite](/Peridotite): Cryptic and Modal Changes

The effects of metasomatism within mantle [peridotite](/Peridotite) are categorized into two primary forms: **modal** and **cryptic**. These distinctions are critical for understanding how the deep [Earth](/Earth) evolves chemically.

In **cryptic metasomatism**, the transformation is subtle, almost insidious. The bulk [mineralogy](/Mineralogy) of the [peridotite](/Peridotite) appears outwardly unchanged to the casual observer. However, the chemical compositions of the existing [minerals](/Mineral) are subtly altered, or newly introduced [chemical elements](/Chemical_element) are concentrated along the grain boundaries of the [minerals](/Mineral). The rock looks the same, but its internal chemistry has been rewired. This type of metasomatism often occurs as rising or percolating melts interact with the surrounding [peridotite](/Peridotite), causing reciprocal changes in the compositions of both the melts and the host rock. At the extreme temperatures found in the mantle, solid-state [diffusion](/Diffusion) also becomes remarkably effective, capable of altering rock compositions over distances of tens of centimeters adjacent to melt conduits. Consequently, gradients in [mineral](/Mineral) composition observed adjacent to [pyroxenite](/Pyroxenite) [dikes](/Dike_(geology)) can serve as compelling evidence of this diffusive, cryptic metasomatic process.

In contrast, **modal metasomatism** is far more overt. It results in the definitive formation of entirely new [minerals](/Mineral) within the [peridotite](/Peridotite) assemblage. The presence of [amphibole](/Amphibole) and [phlogopite](/Phlogopite) [minerals](/Mineral) in [peridotite](/Peridotite) [xenoliths](/Xenoliths) (fragments of mantle rock brought to the surface by [magma](/Magma)) is widely considered strong and unequivocal evidence of significant metasomatic processes having occurred in the mantle. Furthermore, the formation of other [minerals](/Mineral) less common in pristine [peridotite](/Peridotite), such as [dolomite](/Dolomite_(mineral)), [calcite](/Calcite), [ilmenite](/Ilmenite), [rutile](/Rutile), and [armalcolite](/Armalcolite), is also confidently attributed to the action of melt or fluid metasomatism. These new [minerals](/Mineral) are the smoking gun, proof that the rock has been chemically tampered with.

## Metasomatism Schemes: Diffusion vs. Infiltration

Within [granitic](/Granite) systems, two primary schemes are generally invoked to explain the manifestation of metasomatism: **diffusion metasomatism** and **infiltration metasomatism**. [^9] While both involve fluid-rock interaction, their mechanisms of fluid transport and alteration differ significantly.

**Infiltration metasomatism** occurs when metasomatic fluids actively flow through open cracks, fractures, or other pathways that promote robust fluid circulation in areas of high [permeability](/Permeability_(earth_sciences)). The fluid physically moves into the rock, carrying dissolved components with it. [^9] In contrast, **diffusion metasomatism** takes place when fluids are incorporated into the microscopic pores of the rock, and chemical components then migrate through the fluid via concentration gradients. This process is fundamentally determined by the [porosity](/Porosity) of the rock. Rocks altered primarily by infiltration metasomatism will often exhibit less pervasive or more channelized alteration compared to rocks altered by diffusion, largely due to the dispersion effects that occur during fluid advection. [^10] The fluid moves so quickly that the chemical reaction doesn't have time to fully permeate.

These two distinct methods are commonly responsible for the transportation of [chemical elements](/Chemical_element) from one geological region to another. The affected regions can either become enriched or depleted in the transported components, relative to their original, pre-metasomatic state. [^11] The extent and nature of these chemical changes are profoundly influenced by various factors, including the chemical composition of the metasomatic liquid itself, as well as the effects of [chemical weathering](/Weathering). [Chemical weathering](/Weathering) can strongly alter the levels and contents of the metasomatic liquid, thereby impacting the major [element geochemistry](/Geochemistry) and [mineralogy](/Mineralogy) of any associated [siliciclastic sediments](/Siliciclastic_rock). [^12]

## Alteration Assemblages: Common Metasomatic Signatures

Investigations into altered rocks, particularly those associated with [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) [ore deposits](/Ore_deposit), have revealed several ubiquitous types of alteration assemblages. These assemblages form distinct groups of metasomatic effects, characteristic textures, and predictable [mineral](/Mineral) associations, providing a roadmap for understanding the fluid history of an area.

*   **[Propylitic alteration](/Propylitic_alteration)**: This is typically caused by the action of [iron](/Iron) and [sulfur](/Sulfur)-bearing [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) fluids. It commonly results in an [epidote](/Epidote)-[chlorite](/Chlorite_group)-[pyrite](/Pyrite) [mineral assemblage](/Mineral_assemblage), often accompanied by [hematite](/Hematite) and [magnetite](/Magnetite) facies. This alteration is generally considered to be a relatively low-temperature, outer halo around many [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) systems.
*   **Albite-epidote alteration**: This type of alteration is driven by [silica](/Silica)-bearing fluids that are particularly rich in [sodium](/Sodium) and [calcium](/Calcium). The result is typically a weak, sometimes subtle, [albite](/Albite)-[silica](/Silica)-[epidote](/Epidote) assemblage, often replacing original [plagioclase](/Plagioclase) [feldspar](/Feldspar).
*   **Potassic alteration**: Characteristic of many [porphyry copper](/Porphyry_copper) and [lode gold deposits](/Gold_ore), [potassic alteration](/Potassium) involves the introduction of [potassium](/Potassium). In [iron](/Iron)-rich rocks, this leads to the production of micaceous, [potassic](/Potassium) [minerals](/Mineral) such as [biotite](/Biotite). In more [felsic rocks](/Felsic), [muscovite mica](/Muscovite) or [sericite](/Sericite) are formed. Another common manifestation is [orthoclase](/Orthoclase) ([adularia](/Adularia)) alteration, which can be quite pervasive, often producing distinct salmon-pink alteration [vein](/Vein_(geology)) [selvages](/Selvage_(geology)). This is a sign of intense, high-temperature fluid activity.
*   **[Quartz-sericite-pyrite alteration](/Sericitic_alteration)**: In this assemblage, these [minerals](/Mineral) can be deposited both within discrete [veins](/Veins,_metallic_and_mineral) and in a more disseminated manner throughout the host rock. [Sericite](/Sericite), in particular, frequently replaces original [plagioclase](/Plagioclase) [feldspar](/Plagioclase) and [biotite](/Biotite). This alteration type is prevalent in many [porphyry copper](/Porphyry_copper_deposit) and [porphyry molybdenum deposits](/Porphyry_molybdenum_deposit), indicating acidic, sulfur-rich fluids. [^13]
*   **[Argillic alteration](/Argillic_alteration)**: Often found in the more distal, cooler areas of [porphyry deposits](/Porphyry_copper_deposit), [argillic alteration](/Argillic_alteration) represents a lower-temperature assemblage. It involves the conversion of [feldspars](/Feldspar) and some other [minerals](/Mineral) into various [clay minerals](/Clay_mineral) such as [kaolinite](/Kaolinite) and [illite](/Illite). This alteration can frequently overprint older, higher-temperature alteration assemblages, reflecting a later stage of fluid activity or cooling.

Beyond these common types, rarer forms of [hydrothermal](/Hydrothermal) fluids can produce even more specialized metasomatic effects. For instance, highly carbonic fluids can lead to advanced carbonation reactions within the host rock, typical of [calc-silicates](/Calc-silicate). Similarly, [silica](/Silica)-[hematite](/Hematite) fluids are responsible for the production of distinctive [jasperoids](/Jasperoid), [manto ore deposits](/Manto_ore_deposits), and widespread zones of intense [silicification](/Silicification), particularly when interacting with reactive [dolomite](/Dolomite_(rock)) [strata](/Strata). Even the [granitic](/Granite) [plutons](/Pluton) themselves aren't immune, as seen in the Papoose Flat [quartz](/Quartz) [monzonites](/Monzonite), where stressed [minerals](/Mineral) and country rocks are replaced by [porphyroblasts](/Porphyroblast) of [orthoclase](/Orthoclase) and [quartz](/Quartz). [^14] It seems nothing, absolutely nothing, is truly permanent.

